<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB N="1" REF="4">
<HEAD>WHAT we mu&s;t ALL come to.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WOODLEY <HI>and</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dimity.</SPEAKER>
<P>_PO! Po!&mdash;no &s;uch thing&mdash;I tell you, Mr. Woodley, you are a mere novice in the&s;e affairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but li&s;ten to rea&s;on. Mrs. Dimity&mdash;has not your ma&s;ter, Mr. Drugget, invited me down to his country-hou&s;e, in order to give me his daughter Nancy in marriage; and with what pre|tence can he now break off?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>What pretence! &mdash; you put a body out of all patience&mdash;but go on your own way, Sir; my advice is all lo&s;t upon you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come now, do me ju&s;tice&mdash;have not I fix'd an intere&s;t in the young lady's heart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>An intere&s;t in a fiddle&s;tick?&mdash;You ought to have made love to the father and
<PB N="2" REF="5">mother&mdash;what, do you think the way to get a wi&s;e, is by &s;peaking fine things to the lady you've a fancy for?&mdash;That was the practice, indeed, but things are alter'd now&mdash;you mu&s;t addre&s;s the old people, Sir; and never trouble your head about your mi&s;tre&s;s&mdash;None of your letters, and ver&s;es, and &s;oft looks, and fine &s;peeches,&mdash;"Have compa&s;&s;ion, thou angelic crea|ture, on a poor, dying"&mdash;P&s;haw! &s;tuff! non&s;en&s;e! all out of fa&s;hion.&mdash;Go your ways to the old Curmudgeon, humour his whims&mdash;"I &s;hall e&s;teem it an honour, Sir, to be allied to a gentleman of your rank and ta&s;te." "Upon my word, he's a pretty young gentleman."&mdash;Then wheel about to the mother: "Your daughter, Ma'am, is the very model of you, and I &s;hall adore her for your &s;ake." "Here, come hither, Nancy, take this gentleman for better for wor&s;e." "La, Mama, I can never con&s;ent."&mdash;"I &s;hould not have thought of your con&s;ent&mdash;the con&s;ent of your relations is enough: why how now, Hu&s;&s;ey!&mdash;So away you go to church, the knot is tied, and you quarrel like contrary elements all the re&s;t of your lives&mdash;that's the way of the world now."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you know, my dear Dimity, the old couple have received every mark of mention from me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="3" REF="6">
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Attention! to be &s;ure you did not fall a&s;leep in their company; but what then?&mdash;You &s;hould have entered into their cha|racters, play'd with their humours, and &s;a|crificed to their ab&s;urdities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bat if my temper is too frank&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Frank, indeed! I hate the word, except when I receive a letter.&mdash;Have not you to do with a rich old &s;hopkeeper, re|tired from bu&s;ine&s;s with an hundred thou|&s;and pounds in his pocket, to enjoy the du&s;t of the London road, which he calls living in the country&mdash;and yet you mu&s;t find fault with his &s;ituation!&mdash;What if he has made a ridiculous gimcrack of his hou&s;e and gardens, you know his heart is &s;et up|on it; and could not you have commended his ta&s;te? But you mu&s;t be too frank!&mdash;"Tho&s;e walks and alleys are too regular&mdash;tho&s;e evergreens &s;hould not be cut into &s;uch fanta&s;tic &s;hapes."&mdash;And thus you ad|vi&s;e a poor old mechanic, who delights in every thing that's mon&s;trous, to follow nature&mdash;Oh, you're likely to be a &s;ucce&s;s|ful lover!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why &s;hould not I &s;ave a father-in-law from being a laughing-&s;tock?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Make him your father-in-law fir&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why he can't open his windows for the du&s;t&mdash;he &s;tands all day looking thro' a pane of gla&s;s; and he calls that living in the fre&s;h air, and enjoying his own thoughts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="7">
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po! Po!&mdash;you have ruin'd your|&s;elf by talking &s;en&s;e to him; and all your non&s;en&s;e to the daughter won't make amends for it.&mdash;And then the mother; how have you play'd your car<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">s in that quarter?&mdash;She wants a tin&s;el man of fa&s;hion for her &s;econd daughter&mdash;"Don't you &s;ee <STAGE>(&s;ays &s;he)</STAGE> how happy my elde&s;t girl is made by marrying Sir Charles Rackett&mdash;Nancy &s;hall have a man of quality too."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet I know Sir Charles Rac|kett perfectly well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;o do I; and I know he'll make his lady wretched at la&s;t&mdash;But what then? You &s;hould have humour'd the old folks, &mdash;you &s;hould have been a talking empty fop, to the good old lady; and to the old gentleman, an admirer of his ta&s;te in gardening. But you have lo&s;t him&mdash;he is grown fond of this beau Lovelace, that's here in the hou&s;e with him; the coxcomb ingratiates him&s;elf by flattery, and you're undone by frankne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet, Dimity, I won't de&s;pair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet you have rea&s;on, a million of rea&s;ons&mdash;To-morrow is fix'd for the wedding-day; Sir Charles and his lady are to be here this very night&mdash;they are engag'd, indeed, at a great rout in town, but they take a bed here, not with&s;tanding.&mdash;The family is fitting up for them; Mr. Drugget will keep ye all up, in the next room there
<PB N="5" REF="8">till they arrive&mdash;and to-morrow the bu&s;ine&s;s is over&mdash;and yet you don't, de&s;pair!&mdash;Hu&s;h!&mdash;, hold your tongue; here he comes, and Lovelace with him.&mdash;Step this way with me, and, I'll devi&s;e &s;omething, I warrant you.&mdash;'Tis enough to vex a body, to &s;ee an old father and mother marrying their daugh|ter as they plea&s;e, in &s;pite of all I can do.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DRUGGET <HI>and</HI> LOVELACE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you like my hou&s;e and gardens, Mr. Lovelace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! perfectly, Sir; they gratify my ta&s;te of all things. One &s;ees villas where nature reigns in a wild kind of &s;implicity; but then they have no appearance of art, no art at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true, rightly di&s;tingui&s;h'd:&mdash;now mine is all art; no wild nature here; I did it all my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, had you none of the great proficients in gardening to a&s;&s;i&s;t you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lackaday! no, &mdash;ha! ha! I did it all my&s;elf&mdash;I love my garden. The front of my hou&s;e, Mr. Lovelace, is not that very pretty?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Elegant to a degree!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you like the &s;un-dial, plac'd ju&s;t by my dining-room windows?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>A perfect beauty!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="9">
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I knew you'd like it&mdash;and the motto is &s;o well adapted&mdash;<HI>Tempus edax, &amp; index rorum.</HI> And I know the meaning of it&mdash;Time eateth and di&s;covereth all things&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;pretty, Mr. Lovelace!&mdash;I have &s;een people &s;o &s;tare at it as they pa&s;s by&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why now I don't believe there's a nobleman in the kingdom has &s;uch a thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no&mdash;they have got into a fal&s;e ta&s;te.&mdash;I bought that bit of ground, the ether &s;ide of the road&mdash;and it looks very pretty&mdash;I made a duck-pond there, for the lake of the pro&s;pect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charmingly imagin'd!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>My leaden images are well&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>They exceed ancient &s;tatuary.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I love to be &s;urpriz'd at the turn|ing of a walk with an inanimate figure, that looks you full in the face, and can &s;ay no|thing to you, while one is enjoying one's own thoughts&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;Mr. Lovelace, I'll point out a beauty to you&mdash;Ju&s;t by the haw-haw, at the end of my ground, there is a fine Dutch figure, with a &s;cythe in his hand, and a pipe in his mouths&mdash;that's a jewel, Mr. Lovelace.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>That e&s;cap'd me: a thou&s;and thanks for pointing it out&mdash;I ob&s;erve you have two very fine yew-trees before the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lackaday, Sir! they look un|couth&mdash;I have a de&s;ign about them&mdash;I in|tend
<PB N="7" REF="10">&mdash;ha! ha! it will, be very pretty, Mr. Lovelace&mdash;I intendto have them cut into the &s;hape of the two giants at Guild-hall&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Exqui&s;ite!&mdash;Why then they won't look like trees,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, no&mdash;not at all&mdash;I won't have any thing in my garden that looks like what it is&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nobody under&s;tands the&s;e things like you, Mr. Drugget.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lackaday! it's all my delight now&mdash;this is what I have been working for. I have a great improvement to make &s;till&mdash;I propo&s;e to have my evergreens cut into for|tifications! and then I &s;hall have the Moro ca&s;tle, and the Havanna; and then near it &s;hall be &s;hips of myrtle, failing upon &s;eas of box to attack the town: won't that make my place look very rural, Mr. Lovelace?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you have the mo&s;t fertile in|vention, Mr. Drugget.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! this is what I have been working for. I love my garden&mdash;but I mu&s;t beg your pardon for a few moments&mdash;I mu&s;t &s;tep and &s;peak with a famous nur&s;ery-man, who is come to offer me &s;ome choice things&mdash;Do go and join the company, Mr. Lovelace&mdash;my daughter Rackett and Sir Charles will be here pre&s;ently&mdash;I &s;han't go to bed till I &s;ee 'em&mdash;ha! ha!
<PB N="8" REF="11">&mdash;I did all this my&s;elf, Mr. Lovelace&mdash;this is what I have been working for&mdash;I fin'd for Sheriff to enjoy the&s;e things&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor Mr. Drugget! Mynheer Van Thundertentrunck, in his little box at the &s;ide of a dyke, has as much ta&s;te and ele|gance.&mdash;However, if I can but carry off his daughter, if I can rob his garden of that flower&mdash;why then I &s;hall &s;ay, "This is what I have been working for."</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do lend us your a&s;&s;i&s;tance, Mr. Lovelace&mdash;you're a &s;weet gentleman, and love a good-natur'd action.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why how now! what's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>My ma&s;ter is going to cut the two yew-trees into the &s;hape of two devils, I believe; and my poor mi&s;tre&s;s is breaking her heart for it.&mdash;Do, run and advi&s;e him again&s;t it&mdash;&s;he is your friend, you know &s;he is, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, if that's all&mdash;I'll make that matter ea&s;y directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>My mi&s;tre&s;s will be for ever oblig'd to you; and you'll marry her daughter in the morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my rhetoric &s;hall di&s;&s;uade him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, Sir, put him again&s;t dealing with that nur&s;ery-man; Mrs. Drugget hates him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="12">
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does &s;he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mortally.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say no more, the bu&s;ine&s;s is done.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>If he &s;ays one word, old Drugget will never forgive him.&mdash;My brain was at it's la&s;t &s;hift; but if this plot takes&mdash;So, here comes our Nancy.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> NANCY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Dimity, what's to become of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;tars! what makes you up, Mi&s;s?&mdash;I thought you were gone to bed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;hould I go to bed for? only to tumble and to&s;s, and fret, and be unea&s;y&mdash;they are going to marry me, and I am frighted out of my wits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then you're the only young lady within fifty miles round, that would be frighten'd at &s;uch a thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! if they would let me chu&s;e for my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you like Mr. Lovelace?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My mama does, but I don't; I don't mind his being a man of fa&s;hion, not I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, pray, can you do better than follow the fa&s;hion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! I know there's a fa&s;hion for dre&s;&s;ing the hair, and a fa&s;hion for new
<PB N="10" REF="13">bonnets&mdash;but I never heard of a fa&s;hion for the heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, my dear, the heart mo&s;tly follows the fa&s;hion now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does it?&mdash;Pray who &s;ets the fa&s;hion of the heart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>All the fine ladies in London, o'my con&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what's the la&s;t new fa&s;hion, pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why to marry any fop, that has a few deceitful agreeable appearances about him; &s;omething of a pert phra&s;e, a good ope|rator for the teeth, and a tolerable taylor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>And do they marry without lov|ing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! marrying for love has been a great while out of fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then I'll wait till that fa&s;hion comes up again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then, Mr. Lovelace, I reckon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! I don't like him: he talks to me as if he was the mo&s;t mi&s;erable man in the world, and the confident thing looks &s;o pleas'd with him&s;elf all the while.&mdash;I want to marry for love, and not for card-playing&mdash;I &s;hould not be able to bear the life my &s;i&s;ter leads with Sir Charles Rackett&mdash;and I'll forfeit my new cap, if they don't quarrel &s;oon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll be &s;worn they will&mdash;but what &s;ay you then to Mr. Woodley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah!&mdash;I don't know what to &s;ay&mdash;but I can &s;ing &s;omething that will explain, my mind.</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>WHEN fir&s;t the dear youth pa&s;&s;ing by,</L>
<L>Di&s;clos'd his fair form to my &s;ight,</L>
<L>I gaz'd, but I could not tell why;</L>
<L>My heart it went throb with delight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>2.</HEAD>
<L>As nearer he drew, tho&s;e &s;weet eyes</L>
<L>Were with their dear meaning &s;o bright,</L>
<L>I trembled, and, lo&s;t in &s;urprize,</L>
<L>My heart it went throb with delight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3">
<HEAD>3.</HEAD>
<L>When his lips their dear accents did try</L>
<L>The return of my love to excite,</L>
<L>I feign'd, yet began to gue&s;s why</L>
<L>My heart it went throb with delight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4">
<HEAD>4.</HEAD>
<L>We chang'd the &s;tol'n glance, the fond &s;mile,</L>
<L>Which lovers alone read aright;</L>
<L>We look'd, and we &s;igh'd, yet the while</L>
<L>Our hearts they went throb with delight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5">
<HEAD>5.</HEAD>
<L>Con&s;ent I &s;oon blu&s;h'd, with a &s;igh</L>
<L>My promi&s;e I ventur'd to plight;</L>
<L>Come, Hymen, we then &s;hall know why</L>
<L>Our hearts they go throb with delight.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="12" REF="15">
<HI>Enter</HI> WOODLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weete&s;t angel! I have heard all, and my heart overflows with love and gratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! but I did not know you was li&s;tening. You &s;hould not have betray'd me &s;o, Dimity: I &s;hall be angry with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'll take my chance for that.&mdash;Run both into my room, and &s;ay all your pretty things to one another there, for here comes the old gentleman&mdash;make ha&s;te away.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt Woodley and Nancy.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>A forward pre&s;uming coxcomb! Dimity, do you &s;tep to Mrs. Drugget, and &s;end her hither.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir;&mdash;It works upon him I &s;ee.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>The yew-trees ought not to be cut, becau&s;e they'll help to keep off the da&s;t, and I am too near the road already&mdash;a &s;orry ignorant fop!&mdash;When I am in &s;o fine a &s;ituation, and can &s;ee every carriage that goes by.&mdash;And then to abu&s;e the nur&s;ery-man's rarities!&mdash;A finer &s;ucking pig in lavender, with &s;age growing in his belly, was never &s;een!&mdash;And yet he wants me not to have it&mdash;But have it I will.&mdash;
<PB N="13" REF="16">There's a fine tree of knowledge too, with Adam and Eve in juniper; Eve's no&s;e not quite grown, but it's thought in the &s;pring will be very forward&mdash;I'll have that too, with the &s;erpent in ground-ivy&mdash;two poets in wormwood&mdash;I'll have them both. Ay; and there's a Lord Mayor's fea&s;t in honey|&s;uckle; and the whole court of Aldermen in hornbeam: and three modern beaux in je&s;&s;amine, &s;omewhat &s;tunted: they all &s;hall be in my garden, with the Dragon of Wantley in box&mdash;all&mdash;all&mdash;I'll have 'em all, let my wife and Mr. Lovelace &s;ay what they will&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. DRUGGET.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you &s;end for me, lovey?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>The yew-trees &s;hall be cut into the giants of Guild-hall, whether you will or not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sure my own dear will do as he plea&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the pond, tho'you prai&s;e the green banks, &s;hall be wall'd round, and I'll have a little fat boy in marble, &s;pouting up water in the middle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weet, who hinders you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and I'll buy the nur&s;ery-man's whole catalogue&mdash;Do you think after retiring to live all the way here, almo&s;t
<PB N="14" REF="17">four miles from London, that I won't do as I plea&s;e in my own garden?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear but why are you in &s;uch a pa&s;&s;ion?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll have the lavender pig, and the Adam and Eve, and the Dragon of Wantley, and all of 'em&mdash;and there &s;han't be a more romantic &s;pot on the London road then mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;ure it's as pretty as hands can make it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did it all my&s;elf, and I'll do more&mdash;And Mr. Lovelace &s;han't have my daughter.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! what's the matter now, Mr. Drugget?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;hall learn better manners than to abu&s;e my hou&s;e and gardens.&mdash;You put him in the head of it, but I'll di&s;appoint ye both&mdash;And &s;o you may go and tell Mr. Lovelace that the match is quite off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't comprehend all this not I&mdash;but I'll tell him &s;o, if you plea&s;e, my dear&mdash;I am willing to give my&s;elf pain, if it will give you plea&s;ure: mu&s;t I give my|&s;elf pain?&mdash;don't a&s;k me, pray don't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am re&s;olv'd, and it &s;hall be &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let it be &s;o then. <STAGE>(Cries)</STAGE> Oh! oh! cruel man! I &s;hall break my heart if the match is broke off&mdash;if it is not con|cluded to-morrow, &s;end for an undertaker, and bury me the next day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! I don't want that neither&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! oh!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am your lord and matter, my dear, but not your executioner&mdash;Before George, it mu&s;t never be &s;aid that my wife died of too much compliance&mdash;Cheer up, my love&mdash;and this affair &s;hall be &s;ettled as &s;oon as Sir Charles and Lady Rackett arrive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You bring me to life again&mdash;you know, my &s;weet, what an happy couple Sir Charles and his Lady are&mdash;they have been married the&s;e &s;ix weeks, and have never had the lea&s;t difference&mdash;Why &s;hould not we make our Nancy as happy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles and his Lady, Ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! charming! I'm tran&s;|ported with joy!&mdash;Where are they? I long to &s;ee 'em.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir; the happy couple are arriv'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, they do live happy, in|deed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>But how long will it la&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>How long! don't forbode any ill, you jade&mdash;don't, I &s;ay&mdash;It will la&s;t during their lives, I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, mark the end of it&mdash;Sir Charles, I know, is gay. and good-humour'd
<PB N="16" REF="19">&mdash;but he can't bear the lea&s;t contradiction, no, not in the mere&s;t tri&s;le.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue&mdash;hold your tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; I have done;&mdash;and yet there is in the compo&s;ition of Sir Charles a certain humour, which, like the flying gout, gives nodi&s;turbance to the family till it &s;ettles in the head&mdash;When once it fixes there, mercy on very body about him! but here he comes.</P>
<STAGE>Exit,</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Sir, I ki&s;s your hand&mdash;but why &s;tand on ceremony? to find you up thus late, mortifies me beyond ex|pre&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis but once in a way, Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My obligations to you are in|expre&s;&s;ible; you have given me the mo&s;t amiable of girls; our tempers accord like uni&s;ons in mu&s;ic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! that's what makes me happy in my old days; my children and my gar|den are all my care.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And my friend Lovelace&mdash;he is to have our &s;i&s;ter Nancy, I find.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why my wife is &s;o minded.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, by all means, let her be made happy&mdash;A very pretty fellow Lovelace
<PB N="17" REF="20">&mdash;And as to that Mr.&mdash;Woodley I think you call him&mdash;he is but a plain underbred, ill-fa&s;hion'd &s;ort of a&mdash;Nobody knows him, he is not one of us&mdash;Oh, by all means marry her to one of us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I believe it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash;Would you take any refre&s;hment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing in nature&mdash;it is time to retire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well! good night then, Sir Charles&mdash;ha! here comes my daughter&mdash;good night, Sir Charles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bon repos!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Going out)</STAGE> My Lady Rackett, I'm glad to hear how happy you are, <STAGE>(with|out)</STAGE> I won't detain you now&mdash;there's your good man waiting for you&mdash;good night, my girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t humour this old putt, in order to be remember'd in his will.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lady RACKETT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>O la!&mdash;I'm quite fatigu'd&mdash;I can hardly move&mdash;why don't you help me, you barbarous man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>There; take my arm&mdash;"Was ever thing &s;o pretty made to walk."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I won't be laugh'd at&mdash;I don't love you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>No. Dear me! this glove! Why don't you help me off with my glove? p&s;haw!&mdash;Yow aukward thing, let it alone; you an't fit to be about me, I might as well not be married for any u&s;e you are of&mdash;reach me a chair&mdash;You have no compa&s;&s;ion, for me&mdash;I am &s;o glad to &s;it down&mdash;Why do you drag me to routs&mdash;You know I hate 'em?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! there's no exi&s;ting, no breathing, unle&s;s one does as other people of fa&s;hion do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I'm out of humour, I lo&s;t all my money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How much?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three hundred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fret for that&mdash;I don't value three hundred pounds to contribute to your happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you?&mdash;not value three hundred pounds to plea&s;e me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know I don't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! you fond fool!&mdash;but I hate gaming&mdash;It almo&s;t metamorpho&s;es a woman into a fury&mdash;do you know that I was frighted at my&s;elf &s;everal times to-night&mdash;I had an huge oath at the very tip of my tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had ye?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I caught my&s;elf at it&mdash;and &s;o I bit my lips&mdash;and then I was cramm'd up in a corner of the room with &s;uch a &s;trange
<PB N="19" REF="22">party at a whi&s;t-table, looking at black and red &s;pots&mdash;did you mind 'em?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know I was bu&s;y el&s;e where.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>There was that &s;trange unac|countable woman, Mrs. Night&s;hade&mdash;She behav'd &s;o &s;trangely to her hu&s;band, a poor; inoffen&s;ive, good-natur'd, good &s;ort of a good for nothing kind of man, &mdash;but &s;he &s;o teiz'd him&mdash;"How could you play that card? Ah, you've a head, and &s;o has a pin&mdash;You're a num&s;cull, you know you are&mdash;Ma'am, he has the poore&s;t head in the world, he does not know what he is about; you know you don't&mdash;Ah &s;ye!&mdash;I'm a&s;ham'd of you!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has &s;erv'd to divert you, I &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then to crown all&mdash;there was my Lady Clackit, who runs on with an eternal volubility of nothing, out of all &s;ea&s;on, time, and place&mdash;In the very mid&s;t of the game &s;he begins, "Lard, Ma'am, I was apprehen&s;ive I &s;hould not be able to wait on your La'&s;hip&mdash;my poor little dog, Pompey&mdash;the &s;weete&s;t thing in the world, &mdash;a &s;pade led!&mdash;there's the knave&mdash;I was fetching a walk, Me'm, the other morning in the Park&mdash;a fine fro&s;ty morning it was&mdash;I love fro&s;ty weather of all things&mdash;Let me look at the la&s;t trick&mdash;and &s;o Me'm, little Pompey&mdash;And if your La'&s;hip was to &s;ee the dear creature pinch'd with the fro&s;t, and
<PB N="20" REF="23">mincing his &s;teps along the Mall&mdash;with his pretty little innocent face&mdash;I vow I don't know what to play&mdash;And &s;o, Me'm, while I was talking to Captain Flim&s;ey&mdash;Your La'&s;hip knows Captain Flim&s;ey&mdash;Nothing but rubbi&s;h in my hand&mdash;I can't help it&mdash;And &s;o, Me'm, five odious frights of dogs be&s;et my poor little Pompey&mdash;the dear creature has the heart of a lion, but who can re&s;i&s;t five at once&mdash;And &s;o Pompey barked for a&s;&s;i&s;tance&mdash;the hurt he receiv'd was upon his che&s;t&mdash;the doctor would not advi&s;e him to venture out till the wound is heal'd, for fear of an inflammation&mdash;Pray what's trumps?"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, you'd make a mo&s;t excellent actre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now let's go to bed&mdash;but Sir Charles, how &s;hockingly you play'd that la&s;t rubber, when I &s;tood looking over you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My love, I play'd the truth of the same.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, indeed, my dear, you play'd it wrong.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po! non&s;en&s;e! you don't un|der&s;tand it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, I am allow'd to play better then you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>All conceit, my dear, I was perfectly right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;uch thing, Sir Charles, the diamond was the play.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po! po! ridiculous! the club was the card again&s;t the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, no, no, I &s;ay it was the diamond.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! Madam, I &s;ay it was the club.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you fly into &s;uch a pa&s;&s;ion for?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath and fury, do you think I don't know what I'm about? I tell you once more the club was the judgment of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>May be &s;o&mdash;have it your own way <STAGE>(walks about, and &s;ings.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir. Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vexation! you're the &s;trange&s;t woman that ever liv'd, there's no conver&s;|ing with you&mdash;Look'ye here, my Lady Rackett&mdash;it's the cleare&s;t ca&s;e in the world, I'll make it plain in a moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir! ha! ha! ha! <STAGE>(witha &s;neering laugh)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I had four cards left&mdash;a trump was led&mdash;they were &s;ix&mdash;no, no, no, they were &s;even, and we nine&mdash;then you know&mdash;the beauty of the play was to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now it's amazing to me, that you can't &s;ee it&mdash;give me leave, Sir Charles&mdash;your left hand adver&s;ary had led his la&s;t trump&mdash;and he had before fine&s;s'd the club, and rough'd the diamond&mdash;now if you had put on your diamond&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="25">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zoons! Madam, but we play'd for the odd trick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;ure the play for the odd trick&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death and fury! can't you hear me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zoons, hear me I &s;ay&mdash;will you hear me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never heard the like in my life;</P>
<STAGE>(Hums a tune, and walks about fretfully.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then you are enough to provoke the patience of a Stoic&mdash;<HI>(Looks at her, and &s;he walks about, and laughs unea&s;ily.)</HI> Very well, Madam;&mdash;You know no more of the game than a hobby-hor&s;e&mdash;no more than my coachman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha!&mdash; <STAGE>(takes cut a gla&s;s, aud &s;ettles her hair.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a vile woman, and I'll not &s;leep another night under one roof with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>As you plea&s;e, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam it &s;hall be as I plea&s;e&mdash;I'll order my chariot this moment&mdash; <STAGE>(going)</STAGE> I know how the cards &s;hould be play'd as well as any man in England, that let me tell you&mdash; <STAGE>(going)</STAGE>&mdash;And when your family were &s;tanding behind counters, mea&s;uring out tape, and bartering for Whitechapel needles, my ance&s;tors, my ance&s;tors, Madam, were &s;quandering away
<PB N="23" REF="26">whole e&s;tates at cards; whold e&s;tates, my Lady Rackett&mdash; <STAGE>(She hums a tune and he looks at her)</STAGE>&mdash;Why then, by all that's dear to me, I'll never exchange another word with you, good, bad, or indifferent&mdash;Look'ye, my Lady Rackett&mdash;thus it &s;tood&mdash;the trump being led, it was then my bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;ine&s;&s;e the club.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn it, I have done with you for ever, and &s;o you may tell your father.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a pa&s;&s;ion the gentleman's in! ha! ha! <STAGE>(laughs in a peevi&s;h manner)</STAGE>, I promi&s;e him, I'll not give up my judgment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lady Rackett, look'ye, Ma'am&mdash;once more out of pure good-nature&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I am convinc'd of your good|nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>That, and that only prevails with me to tell you, the club was the play.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, be it &s;o&mdash;I have no ob|jection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's the cleare&s;t point in the world&mdash;we were niney and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>And for that very rea&s;oh:&mdash;you know the club was the be&s;t in the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no &s;uch thing as talking to you&mdash;You're a ba&s;e woman&mdash;I'll part from you for ever; you may live here with
<PB N="24" REF="27">your father, and admire his fanta&s;tical ever|greens, till you grow as fanta&s;tical your&s;elf&mdash;I'll &s;et out for London this in&s;tant&mdash; <STAGE>(Stops at the door)</STAGE> The club was not the be&s;t in the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>How calm you are! Well!&mdash;I'll go to bed;&mdash;will you come?&mdash;you had better&mdash;come then&mdash;you &s;hall come to bed&mdash;not come to bed when I a&s;k you?&mdash;Poor Sir Charles!</P>
<STAGE>Looks and laughs, then Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>That ea&s;e is provoking. <STAGE>(Cros;&s;es to the oppo&s;ite door, where &s;he went out)</STAGE>&mdash;I tell you the diamond was the play, and I here take my final leave of you&mdash; <STAGE>(walks back, as fa&s;t as be can)</STAGE> I am re&s;olv'd upon it, and I know the club was not the be&s;t in the hou&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dimity.</SPEAKER>
<P>HA! ha! ha! oh! heavens! I &s;hall ex|pire in a fit of laughing&mdash;This is the modi&s;h couple that were &s;o happy&mdash;&s;uch a quarrel as they have had&mdash;the whole hou&s;e is in an uproar&mdash;ha! ha! A rare proof of the happiness they enjoy in high life. I &s;hall
<PB N="25" REF="28">never hear people of fa&s;hion mention'd again, but I &s;hall be ready to die in a fit of laughter&mdash;ho! ho! ho!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! how! what's the matter, Di|mity&mdash;What am I call'd down &s;tairs for?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why there's two people of fa&s;hion&mdash; <STAGE>(Stifles a laugh.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you &s;aucy minx!&mdash;Explain this moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>The fond couple have been to|gether by the ears this half hour&mdash;are you &s;atisfied now?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay!&mdash;what have they quarrell'd&mdash;what was it about?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Something above my comprehen|&s;ion and your's too, I believe&mdash;People in high life under&s;tand their own forms be&s;t&mdash;And here comes one that can unriddle the whole affair.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(To the people within)</STAGE> I &s;ay, let the hor&s;es be put-to this moment&mdash;So, Mr. Drugget.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Charles, here's a terrible bu&s;tle&mdash;I did not expect this&mdash;what ean be the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="29">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been us'd by your daughter, in &s;o ba&s;e, &s;o contemptuous a manner, that I am determin'd not to &s;tay in this hou&s;e to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a thunder-bolt to me! after &s;eeing how elegantly and fa&s;hionably you liv'd together, to find new all &s;un&s;hine vani&s;h'd&mdash;Do, Sir Charles, let me heal this breach, if po&s;&s;ible.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, 'tis impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;I'll not live with her a day longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, don't be over ha&s;ty, &mdash;let me intreat you, go to bed and &s;leep upon it&mdash;in the morning when you're cool&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir, I am very cool, I a&s;&s;ure&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;it is not in her power, Sir, to&mdash;to&mdash;a&mdash;a&mdash;to di&s;turb the &s;erenity of my temper&mdash;Don't imagine that I'm in apa&s;&s;ion&mdash;I'm not &s;o ea&s;ily ruffled as you may ima|gine&mdash;But quietly and deliberately. I can re&s;ent ill u&s;age&mdash;I can repay the injuries done me by a fal&s;e, ungrateful, deceitful wife, with the &s;everity, and at the &s;ame time with the compo&s;ure of an old judge, harden'd in his office&mdash;That man, am, I, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>The injuries done you by a trea|cherous wife!&mdash;my daughter I hope&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her character is now fully known to me&mdash;&s;he's a vile woman! that's all I have to &s;ay, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="27" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey! how!&mdash;a vile woman&mdash;what has &s;he done&mdash;I hope &s;he is not capable&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall enter into no detail, Mr. Drugget, the time and circum&s;tances won't allow it at pre&s;ent&mdash;But depend upon it I have done with her&mdash;a low, unpoli&s;h'd, un|educated, fal&s;e, impo&s;ing&mdash;See if the hor&s;es are put-to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on me! in my old days to hear this.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deliver me! I am all over in &s;uch a tremble&mdash;Sir Charles, I &s;hall break my heart if there's any thing ami&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I am very &s;orry for your &s;ake&mdash;but there is no po&s;&s;ibility of living with her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor dear girl! What can &s;he have done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What all her &s;ex can do, the very &s;pirit of them all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay! ay! ay!&mdash;She's bringing &s;oul di&s;grace upon us&mdash;This comes of her mar|rying a man of fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faihion, Sir!&mdash;That &s;hould have in&s;tructed her better&mdash;She might have been &s;en&s;ible of her happine&s;s&mdash;Whatever you may think of the fortune you gave her, my rank in life, claims re&s;pect&mdash;claims obe|dience,
<PB N="28" REF="31">attention, truth, and love, from one rai&s;ed in the world as &s;he has been by an alliance with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And let me tell you, however you may e&s;timate your quality, my daughter is dear to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And, Sir, my character is dear to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet you mu&s;t give me leave to tell you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't hear a word.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not in behalf of my own daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing can excu&s;e her&mdash;'tis to no purpo&s;e&mdash;She has married above her; and if that circum&s;tance makes the Lady forget her&s;elf, &s;he at lea&s;t &s;hall &s;ee that I can and will &s;upport my own dignity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Sir, I have a right to a&s;k&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Patience, my dear, be a little calm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mrs. Drugget, do you have pa|tience, I mu&s;t and will enquire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be &s;o ha&s;ty, my love; have &s;ome re&s;pect for Sir Charles's rank; don't be violent with a man of his fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue, woman, I &s;ay&mdash;you're not a per&s;on of fa&s;hion at lea&s;t&mdash;My daughter was ever a good girl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have found her out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! then it's all over&mdash;and it does not &s;ignify arguing about it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That ever I &s;hould live to &s;ee this hour!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know her thoroughly&mdash;and there is no &s;uch thing as being connected with her a moment longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>How the unfortunate girl could take &s;uch wickedne&s;s in her head, I can't imagine&mdash;I'll go and &s;peak to the un|happy creature this moment.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;tands detected now&mdash;de|tected in her true&s;t colours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, grievous as it may be, let me hear the circum&s;tances of this unhappy bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Drugget, I have not lei&s;ure now&mdash;but her behaviour has been &s;o exa&s;|perating, that I &s;hall make the be&s;t of my way to town&mdash;My mind is fixed&mdash;She &s;ees me no more, and &s;o, your &s;ervant, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a calamity has here befallen us! as good a girl, and as well di&s;pos'd till the evil communication of high life, and fa&s;hionable vices, turn'd her to folly.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LOVELACE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Joy! joy! Mr. Drugget, I give you joy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't in&s;ult me, Sir&mdash;I de&s;ire you won't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ult you, Sir!&mdash;is there any thing in&s;ulting, my dear Sir, if I take the liberty to congratulate you on&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>There! there!&mdash;the manners of high life for you&mdash;He thinks there's no|thing in all this&mdash;the ill behaviour of a wife he thinks an ornament to her character&mdash;Mr. Lovelace, you &s;hall have no daughter of mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Sir, never bear malice&mdash;I have recon&s;ider'd the thing, and cur&s;e catch me if I don't think your notion of the Gulid-hall giants, and the court of Alder|men in hornbeam&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! well! well! there may be people of the court end of the town in hornbeam too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, faith, &s;o there may&mdash;and I believe I could recommend you a tolerable collection&mdash;however, with your daughter I am ready to venture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I am not ready&mdash;I'll not ven|ture my girl with you&mdash;no more daughters of mine &s;hall have their minds deprav'd by polite vices.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WOODLEY.</STAGE>
<P>Mr. Woodley&mdash;you &s;hall have Nancy to your wife, as I promis'd you&mdash;take her to|morrow morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I have not words to expre&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil is the matter with the old haberda&s;her now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And hark ye, Mr. Woodley&mdash;I'll make you a pre&s;ent for your garden, of a coronation dinner in greens, with the cham|pion riding on hor&s;eback, and the &s;word will be full grown before April next.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall receive it, Sir, as your favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay! I &s;ee my error in want|ing an alliance with great folks&mdash;I had ra|ther have you, Mr.Woodley, for my &s;on-in-law, than any courtly fop of 'em all. Is this man gone!&mdash;Is Sir Charles Rackett gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not yet;&mdash;he makes a bawling yonder for his hor&s;es&mdash;I'll &s;tep and call him to you.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am out of all patience&mdash;I am out of my &s;en&s;es, &mdash;I mu&s;t &s;ee him once more&mdash;Mr. Lovelace, you nor no per&s;on of fa&s;hion, &s;hall ruin another daughter of mine.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Droll this!&mdash;damn'd droll! And every &s;yllable of it Arabic to me&mdash;the queer old putt is as whim&s;ical in his notions of life as of gardening. If this be the ca&s;e&mdash;I'll bru&s;h, and leave him to his exotics.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="32" REF="35"><HI>Enter</HI> Lady RACKETT, Mrs. DRUGGET, <HI>and</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>A cruel barbarous man! to quarrel in this unaccountable manner; to alarm the whole hou&s;e, and expo&s;e me and him&s;elf too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! child! I never thought it would have come to this&mdash;your &s;hame won't end here; it will be all over St. James's pari&s;h by to-morrow morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, if it mu&s;t be &s;o, there's one comfort, the &s;tory will tell more to his di&s;grace than mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I'm a &s;inner, and &s;o it will, Madam. He de&s;erves what he has met with, I think.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dimity, don't you encourage her&mdash;No, no, no, my dear child, the dis|grace will be all your own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will it?&mdash;I am &s;ure I &s;han't blu&s;h for any thing that has pa&s;t&mdash;I know a little more of the world than that comes to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hock me to hear you &s;peak &s;o&mdash;I did not think you had been &s;o harden'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Harden'd do you call it?&mdash;I have Iiv'd in the world to very little purpo&s;e, if &s;uch trifles as the&s;e are to di&s;turb my re&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="36">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You wicked girl!&mdash;Do you call it a trifle to be guilty of fal&s;hood to your hu&s;|band's bed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash; <STAGE>(Turns &s;hort, and &s;lares at her.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>That! that's a mere trifle indeed&mdash;I have been in as good places as any body, and not a creature minds it now, I'm &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lady Rackett, my Lady Rackett, I never could think to &s;ee you come to this deplorable &s;hame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely the ba&s;e man has not been capable of laying any thing of that &s;ort to my charge&mdash; <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> All this is unaccount|able to me&mdash;hai ha!&mdash;'tis ridiculous be|yond mea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, Madam:&mdash;Laugh at it&mdash;you &s;erv'd him right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charlotte! Charlotte! 'm a&s;toni&s;h'd at your wickedne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I prote&s;t and vow I don't comprehend all this&mdash;has Sir Charles ac|cus'd me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! too true he has&mdash;he has found you out, and you have behav'd ba&s;ely he &s;ays.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have fallen into frailty like many others of your &s;ex, he &s;ays, and he is re&s;olv'd to come to a &s;eparation directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then if he is &s;o ba&s;e a wretch as to di&s;honour me in that manner, his heart &s;hall ake before I live with him again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold to that, Ma'am, and let his head ake into the bargain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! what &s;hall I do? it is all too true I find.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>True!&mdash;'tis fal&s;e as &s;candal, and the vile&s;t calumny that ever was invented.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po! never go to deny it&mdash;own it Ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand away;&mdash;don't talk to me&mdash;Sir Charles! Sir Charles!&mdash;Pray, Madam, let Mr. Woodley have my &s;i&s;ter&mdash;I am unfortunate ever to have &s;een &s;o vile a &s;lan|derer&mdash;is it po&s;&s;ible that he could have talked thus meanly of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your poor father heard it as well as me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then let your doors be open'd for him this very moment&mdash;let him return to London&mdash;if he does not, I'll lock my&s;elf up, and the fal&s;e one &s;han't approach me, tho' he beg on his knees at my very door&mdash;a ba&s;e injurous man!</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dimity, do let us follow, and hear what &s;he has to &s;ay for her&s;elf.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>She has excu&s;e enough I warrant her&mdash;What a noi&s;e is here indeed!&mdash;I have liv'd in polite families, where there was no &s;uch ba&s;tie made about nothing.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES, <HI>and</HI> DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tis in vain Sir, my re&s;olution is taken&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="35" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but con&s;ider, I am her fa|ther, &mdash;indulge me only till we hear what the girl has to &s;ay in her defence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>She can have nothing to &s;ay&mdash;no excu&s;e can palliate &s;uch behaviour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be too po&s;itive&mdash;there may be &s;ome mi&s;take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No mi&s;take&mdash;did not I &s;ee her, hear her my&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lackaday! I am an unfortunate man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>She will be unfortunate too&mdash;with all my heart&mdash;She may thank her&s;elf&mdash;She might have been happy had &s;he been &s;o di&s;pos'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why truly, I think &s;he might.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you'd moderate your an|ger a little&mdash;and let us talk over this affair with temper&mdash;my daughter denies every tittle of your charge.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Denies it! denies it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>She does indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And that aggravates her fault.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>She vows you never found her out in any thing that was wrong.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! She does not allow it to be wrong then!&mdash;Madam, I tell you again, I know her thoroughly, I &s;ay I have found her out, and I am now acquainted with her character.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="36" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>Mrs D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then ycu are in oppo&s;ite &s;tories&mdash;She &s;wears, my dear Mr. Drugget, the poor girl &s;wears &s;he never was guilty of the &s;malle&s;t infidelity to her hu&s;band's bed in her born days.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what then?&mdash;What if &s;he does &s;ay &s;o!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And if &s;he &s;ays truly, it is hard her character &s;hould be blown upon with|out ju&s;t cau&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And is &s;he therefore to behave ill in other re&s;pects? I never charg'd her with infidelity to me, Madam&mdash;there I allow her innocent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And did not you charge her then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, 1 never dreamt of &s;uch a thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, if &s;he's innocent, let me tell you, you're a &s;candalous per&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee, my dear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be quiet&mdash;tho' he is a man of quality, I will tell him of it&mdash;did not I fine for &s;heriff?&mdash;yes, you are a &s;candalous per&s;on to defame an hone&s;t man's daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>What have you taken into your head now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>You charg'd her with fal&s;hood to your bed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;never&mdash;never.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I &s;ay you did&mdash;you call'd your&s;elf a cuckold&mdash;did not he, wife?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Lovey, I'm witne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="40">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po! po! po! no &s;uch thing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I aver you did&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You did indeed, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I tell you no&mdash;po&s;itively, no.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug. and Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I &s;ay yes&mdash;po&s;itively yes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath, this is all madne&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;aid you had found her out in the very fact&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Drugget&mdash;give me leave, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;he follow'd the ways of mo&s;t of her &s;ex&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aid &s;o&mdash;and what then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>There he owns it&mdash;owns that he call'd him&s;elf a cuckold&mdash;and without rhyme or rea&s;on into the bargain&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never own'd any &s;uch thing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>You own'd it even now&mdash;now&mdash;now&mdash;now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DIMITY, <HI>in a fit of laughing.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you think it was all about&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;the whole &s;ecret is come out, ha! ha!&mdash;It was all about a game of cards&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>A game of cards!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P><HI>Dim.</HI> <STAGE>(Laughing)</STAGE> It was all about a club and a diamond <STAGE>(runs out laughing.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And was that all, Sir Charles?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And enough too, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And was that what you found her out in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't bear to be contradicted, when I'm clear that I'm in the right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh!&mdash;I under&s;tand the affair now&mdash;this was only one of tho&s;e polite dis|putes, which people of quality, who have nothing el&s;e to differ about, mu&s;t always be liable to.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never heard of &s;uch a heap of non&s;en&s;e in all my life&mdash;Woodley &s;hall marry Nancy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be in a hurry, my love, this will be all made up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why does not he go and a&s;k her pardon then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg her pardon! I won't de|ba&s;e my&s;elf to any of you&mdash;I &s;han't forgive her, you may re&s;t a&s;&s;ur'd&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now there&mdash;there's a pretty fellow for you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;tep and prevail on my Lady Rackett to &s;peak to him&mdash;then all will be well.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>A ridiculous fop! I'm glad it's no wor&s;e however.
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> NANCY.</STAGE>
So Nancy&mdash;you &s;eem in confu&s;ion, my girl!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can one help it?&mdash;With all this noi&s;e in the hou&s;e, and you're going to
<PB N="39" REF="42">marry me as ill as my &s;i&s;ter&mdash;I hate Mr. Lovelace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know the&s;e people of quality de&s;|pi&s;e us all out of pride, and would be glad to marry us out of avarice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>The girl's right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>They marry one woman, live with another, and love only them&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then quarrel about a card.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't want to be a gay lady&mdash;I want to be happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o you &s;hall&mdash;don't fright your&s;elf, child&mdash;&s;tep to your &s;i&s;ter, bid her make her&s;elf ea&s;y&mdash;go, and comfort her, go&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;tep and &s;ettle the matter with Mr. Woodley this moment.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES, <HI>with a pack' of cards in his hand.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never was any thing like her be|haviour&mdash;I can pick out the very cards I had in my hand, and then 'tis as plain as the &s;un&mdash;there&mdash;now&mdash;there&mdash;no&mdash;damn it&mdash;no&mdash;there it was&mdash;now let's &s;ee&mdash;They had four by honours&mdash;and we play'd for the odd trick&mdash;damnation! honours were divided&mdash;ay!&mdash;honours were divided&mdash;and then a trump was led&mdash;and the other &s;ide had the&mdash;confu&s;ion!&mdash;this prepo&s;terous woman has
<PB N="40" REF="43">put it all out of my head <STAGE>(puts the cards in|to his pocket.)</STAGE> Mighty well, Madam; I have done with you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Sir Charles, let me prevail&mdash;come with me and &s;peak to her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't de&s;ire to &s;ee her face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you were to &s;ee her all bath'd in tears, I am &s;ure it would melt your very heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, it &s;hall be my fault if ever I'm &s;o treated again&mdash;I'll have nothing to &s;ay to her <STAGE>(going, &s;tops)</STAGE> does &s;he give up the point?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>She does, &s;he agrees to an thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does &s;he allow that the club was the play?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t as you plea&s;e&mdash;She's all &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll &s;tep and &s;peak to her&mdash;I never was clearer in any thing in my life.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord love 'em, they'll make it up now&mdash;and then they'll be as happy as ever.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> NANCY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! they may talk what they will of ta&s;te, and genteel life&mdash;I don't think it's natural&mdash;give me Mr. Woodley&mdash;La! there's that odious thing coming this way.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="41" REF="44"><HI>Enter</HI> LOVELACE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>My charming little innocent, I have not &s;een you the&s;e three hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been very happy the&s;e three hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;weet angel, you &s;eem di&s;con|certed&mdash;And you neglect your pretty figure&mdash;no matter for the pre&s;ent; in a little time I &s;hall make you appear as graceful and gen|teel as your &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is not what employs my thoughts, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, but my pretty little dear, that, &s;hou'd engage your attention&mdash;to &s;et off and adorn the charms that nature has given you, &s;hould be the bu&s;ine&s;s of your life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! but I have learnt a new &s;ong that contradicts what you &s;ay, and tho' I am not in a very good humour for &s;inging, yet you &s;hall hear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>By all means;&mdash;dont check your fancy&mdash;I am all attention.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Nan.</SPEAKER>
<P>It expre&s;&s;es my &s;entiments, and when you have heard them you won't teize me any more.</P>
<Q><TEXT LANG="eng">
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>TO dance, and to dre&s;s, and to flaunt it about,</L>
<L>To run to Park, play, to a&s;&s;embly and rout,</L>
<L><PB N="42" REF="45">To wander for ever in whim's giddy maze,</L>
<L>And one poor hair torture a million of ways,</L>
<L>To put, at the gla&s;s, ev'ry feature to &s;chool,</L>
<L>And practi&s;e their art on each fop and each fool,</L>
<L>Of one thing to think, and another to tell,</L>
<L>The&s;e, the&s;e are the manners of each giddy belle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<HEAD>2.</HEAD>
<L>To &s;mile, and to &s;imper, white teeth to di&s;play;</L>
<L>The time in gay follies to trifle away;</L>
<L>Again&s;t ev'ry virtue the bo&s;om to &s;teel,</L>
<L>And only of dre&s;s the anxieties feel;</L>
<L>To be at Eve's ear, the in&s;idious decoy,</L>
<L>The plea&s;ure ne'er ta&s;te yet the mi&s;chief enjoy,</L>
<L>To boa&s;t of &s;oft raptures they never can know,</L>
<L>The&s;e, the&s;e are the manners of each giddy beau. <STAGE>Exit.</STAGE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t have her notwith&s;tanding this&mdash;for tho' I am not in love, yet I'm in debt.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, Mr. Lovelace! any news from above-&s;tairs? Is this ab&s;urd quarrel at an end&mdash;have they made it up?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! a mere bagatelle, Sir&mdash;the&s;e little fracas among the better &s;ort of people never left long&mdash;elegant trifles cau&s;e elegant di&s;putes, and we come together elegantly again&mdash;as you &s;ee&mdash;for here they come, in perfect good humour.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="43" REF="46"><HI>Enter</HI> Sir CHARLES <HI>and</HI> Lady RACKETT, Mrs. DRUGGET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Drugget, I embrace you, Sir; you &s;ee me now in the mo&s;t perfect harmony of &s;pirits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, all reconcil'd again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>All made up, Sir&mdash;I knew how to bring the gentleman to&mdash;this is the fir&s;t difference, I think we ever had, Sir Charles.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll be &s;worn it &s;hall be the la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am at ea&s;e again&mdash;Sir Charles, I can &s;pare you an image to put on the top of your hou&s;e in London.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Infinitely oblig'd to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, they are as happy now as two intriguing ducks in our pond yonder&mdash;You'll give Nancy, to Mr. Love|lace?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, to be &s;ure, my friend Love|lace mu&s;t be the man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then my &s;i&s;ter and I &s;hall be near neighbours, and we &s;hall &s;o rival each other in the beau monde.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! well! I believe it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash;we'll talk of the&s;e matters in the morn|ing&mdash;It's time to retire now&mdash;I am glad to &s;ee you happy again&mdash;and now I'll wi&s;h you a good night, Sir Charles&mdash;Mr. Lovelace,
<PB N="44" REF="47">this is your way&mdash;fare ye well both&mdash;I am glad your quarrels are at an end&mdash;This way, Mr. Lovelace&mdash;come, come my dear&mdash;come, we'll go and take care of one another.</P>
<STAGE>Exeunt Lovelace, Drugget, and Mrs. Drugrret.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! your a &s;ad man, Sir Charles, to behave to me as you have done&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, I grant it&mdash;and &s;uch an ab&s;urd quarrel too&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;about &s;uch a trifle&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's plea&s;ant how we could both fall into &s;uch an error&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ridiculous beyond expre&s;&s;ion, &mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then the mi&s;take your father and mother fell into&mdash;ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>That too is a diverting part of the &s;tory&mdash;ha! ha! but Sir Charier, mu&s;t I I &s;tay and live with my father till I grow as fanta&s;tical as his own evergreens?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, prithee&mdash;don't remind me of my folly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! my relations were all &s;tanding behind counters &s;elling White|chapel needles, while your family were &s;pending great e&s;tates.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, &s;pare my blu&s;hes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>How could you &s;ay &s;o low a thing?&mdash;I don't love you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was indelicate I grant it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I a vile woman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir. Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you, my angel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;han't forgive you!&mdash;I'll have you on your knees for this. <STAGE>(Sings and plays with him.)</STAGE>&mdash;("Go, naughty man")&mdash;Ah! Sir Charles&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>The re&s;t of my life &s;hall aim at convincing you how &s;incerely I love&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Sings)</STAGE> "Go, naughty man, I can't abide you"&mdash;Well! come let us go to re&s;t <STAGE>(Going.)</STAGE> Ah, Sir Charles!&mdash;now it's all over, the diamond was the play&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no, no, no, &mdash;my dear! ha! ha!&mdash;It was the club indeed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, my love, you're mi&s;|taken&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, no, no,&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I &s;ay, yes, yes, yes&mdash; <STAGE>(Both laughing.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw, no &s;uch thing&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis &s;o, indeed&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;no&mdash;no&mdash;you'll make me die with laughing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and you make me laugh too&mdash;ha! ha! <STAGE>(Toying with him.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FOOTMAN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Footm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your honour's cap and &s;lippers&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, give me my night cap&mdash;and here, take the&s;c &s;hoes off <STAGE>(He takes 'em off, and leaves 'em at a di&s;iance)</STAGE> Indeed my
<PB N="46" REF="49">Lady Rackett, you make me ready to expire with laughing&mdash;ba! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may laugh&mdash;but I'm right notwith&s;tanding&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you &s;ay &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you &s;ay otherwi&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well now mind me, my Lady Rackett&mdash;We can now talk of this matter in good humour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>So we can&mdash;and it's for that rea&s;on I venture to &s;peak to you&mdash;are the&s;e the ruffles I bought for you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>They are, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>They are very pretty&mdash;but in|deed you play'd the card wrong&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po, there is nothing &s;o clear&mdash;if you will but hear me&mdash;only hear me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah!&mdash;but do you hear me&mdash;the thing was thus&mdash;your club being the be&s;t in the hou&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you talk &s;o!&mdash; <STAGE>(Some|what peevi&s;h.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>See there now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now &s;ee&mdash;this was the affair&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! fiddle&s;tick! hear me fir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Po&mdash;no&mdash;damn it&mdash;let me &s;peak&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, to be &s;ure you're a &s;trange man&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plague and torture!&mdash;there is no &s;uch thing as conver&s;ing with you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="50">
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Sir&mdash;fly out again&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look here now&mdash;here's a pack of cards&mdash;now you &s;hall be convinc'd&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may talk till to-morrow, I know I'm right <STAGE>(walks about.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then by all that's perver&s;e, you are the mo&s;t head&s;trong&mdash;Can't you look here now&mdash;here are the very cards&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on; you'll find it out at la&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn it! will you let a man &s;hew you! Po! it's all non&s;en&s;e&mdash;I'll talk no more about it&mdash; <STAGE>(Puts up the cards.)</STAGE> Come, we'll go to bed <STAGE>(Going.)</STAGE> Now only &s;tay a moment&mdash; <STAGE>(Takes out the cards)</STAGE>&mdash;Now, mind me&mdash;&s;ee here&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, it does not &s;ignify&mdash;your head will be clearer in the morning&mdash;I'll go to bed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay a moment, can't ye&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;my head begins to ake&mdash; <STAGE>(Affectedly.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then damn the cards&mdash;there&mdash;there&mdash; <STAGE>(Throwing the cards about.)</STAGE> and there, and there&mdash;you may go to bed by your&s;elf&mdash;and confu&s;ion &s;eize me, If I live a moment longer with you&mdash; <STAGE>(Putting on his &s;hoes again.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DIMITY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you call, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;never&mdash;never&mdash;Madam&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(In a fit of laughing)</STAGE>&mdash;What, at it again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take your own way, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now then I tell you once more you are a vile woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dim.</SPEAKER>
<P>Law! Sir&mdash;This is charming!&mdash;I'll run and tell the old couple.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Still putting on his &s;hoes)</STAGE>&mdash;You are the mo&s;t perver&s;e ob&s;tinate, non&s;en&s;ical&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! don't make me laugh again, Sir Charles&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hell and the devil&mdash;will you &s;it down quietly and let me convince you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't chu&s;e to hear any more about it&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, I believe you are po&s;&s;e&s;s'd&mdash;it is in vain to talk &s;en&s;e and rea&s;on to you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you for your compli|ment, Sir&mdash;&s;uch a man <STAGE>(With a &s;neering laugh)</STAGE> I never knew the like&mdash; <STAGE>(Sits down.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>I promi&s;e you, you &s;hall repent of this u&s;age&mdash;before you have a moment of my company again&mdash;it &s;han't be in a hurry you may depend, Madam&mdash;Now &s;ee here&mdash;I can prove it to a demon&s;tration <STAGE>(Sits down by her, &s;he gets up.)</STAGE> Lookye there again now&mdash;you have the mo&s;t perver&s;e and peevi&s;h temper&mdash;I wi&s;h I had never &s;een your face&mdash;I wi&s;h I was a thou&s;and miles off from you&mdash;&s;it down but one moment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm di&s;pos'd to walk about, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then may I peri&s;h if ever&mdash;a blockhead&mdash;an ideot I was to marry <STAGE>(Walks about)</STAGE> &s;uch a provoking&mdash;imper|tinent&mdash; <STAGE>(She &s;its down.)</STAGE>&mdash;Damnation!&mdash;I am &s;o clear in the thing&mdash;She is not worth my notice&mdash; <STAGE>(Sits down, turns his back, and looks unea&s;y.)</STAGE> I'll take no more pains about it&mdash; <STAGE>(Pau&s;es for &s;ome time, then looks at her.)</STAGE> Is not it very &s;trange, that you won't hear me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir I am very ready to hear you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well then&mdash;very well&mdash;you remember how the game &s;tood&mdash;I'll write it down and &s;end it to Arthur's; and if the be&s;t judges there&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you'd untie my necklace, it hurts me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why can't you li&s;ten?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you it hurts me terribly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Cha.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death and confu&s;ion!&mdash;there is no bearing this&mdash;farewell&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mr. <HI>and</HI> Mrs. DRUGGET, WOODLEY, LOVELACE, <HI>and</HI> NANCY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's here to do now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never was &s;uch a man born&mdash;I did not &s;ay a word to the gentleman&mdash;and yet he has been raving about the room like a madman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>And about a club again, I &s;up|po&s;e,
<PB N="50" REF="53">come hither, Nancy; Mr. Woodley, &s;he is yours for life&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, how can you he &s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall be &s;o&mdash;take her for life, Mr. Woodley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wood.</SPEAKER>
<P>My whole life &s;hall be devoted to her happine&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Love.</SPEAKER>
<P>The devil! and &s;o I am to be left in the lurch in this manner, am I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady R.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my dear Sir, this is no|thing&mdash;I have a lure to bring the gentleman back again&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Drug.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never tell me&mdash;it's too late now&mdash;Mr. Woodley, I recommend my girl to your care&mdash;I &s;hall have nothing now to think of, but my greens, and my images, and my &s;hrubbery&mdash;tho', mercy on all married folks, &s;ay I!&mdash;for the&s;e wranglings are, I am afraid, <HI>What we mu&s;t All come to.</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Lady Rackett, coming forward.</STAGE>
<SP>
<L><HI>WHAT we mu&s;t all come to?</HI> What?&mdash;Come to what?</L>
<L>Mu&s;t broils and quarrels be the marriage lot?</L>
<L>If that's the wi&s;e, deep meaning of our poet,</L>
<L>The man's a fool! a blockhead! and I'll &s;hew it.</L>
<L>What could induce him in an age &s;o nice&mdash;</L>
<L>So fam'd for virtue, &s;o refin'd from vice,</L>
<L>To form a plan &s;o trivial, fal&s;e, and low?</L>
<L>As if a belle could quarrel with a beau:</L>
<L><PB N="51" REF="54">As if there were&mdash;in the&s;e thrice happy days,</L>
<L>One who from nature, or from rea&s;on &s;trays!</L>
<L>There's no cro&s;s hu&s;band now; no wrang|ling wife,&mdash;</L>
<L>The man is downright ignorant of life.</L>
<L>'Tis the millennium this&mdash;devoid of guile,</L>
<L>Fair gentle Truth, and white-rob'd Can|dour &s;mile.</L>
<L>From every brea&s;t the forbid love of gold</L>
<L>Is bani&s;h'd quite&mdash;no boroughs now are &s;old!</L>
<L>Fray tell me, Sirs&mdash;(for I don't know, I vow,)</L>
<L>Pray&mdash;is there &s;uch a thing as Gaming now?</L>
<L>Do peers make laws again&s;t that giant Vice,</L>
<L>And then at Arthur's break them in a trice?</L>
<L>No&mdash;no&mdash;our lives are virtuous all, au&s;tere and hard;&mdash;</L>
<L>Pray, ladies, &mdash;do you ever &s;ee a card?</L>
<L>Tho&s;e empty boxes &s;hew you don't love plays;</L>
<L>The managers, poor &s;ouls! get nothing now a days.</L>
<L>If here you come&mdash;by chance&mdash;but once a week,</L>
<L>The pit can witne&s;s that you never &s;peak:</L>
<L>Pen&s;ive Attention &s;its with decent mien;</L>
<L>No paint, no naked &s;houlders to be &s;een!</L>
<L>And yet this grave, this moral, pious age,</L>
<L>May learn one u&s;eful le&s;&s;on from the &s;tage.</L>
<L>Shun &s;trife, ye fair, and once a conte&s;t o'er,</L>
<L>Wake to a blaze the dying flame no more&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="52" REF="55">From fierce debate &s;ly all the tender Love,</L>
<L>And Venus cries, "Coachman, &mdash;Put-to my doves."</L>
<L>The genial bed no blooming Grace prepares,</L>
<L>"And every day becomes a day of cares."</L>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
